    "narrative": "Our lineup for today, April 28, is headlined by **Vinnie Pasquantino**, who sits atop our projections with a 76.21 efficiency score. Facing Civale, **Vinnie Pasquantino** benefits from a massive 14% platoon edge and favorable park conditions, making him our primary anchor for RBI and batting average today. Joining him in the elite tier are **Seiya Suzuki** (67.76) and **Corbin Carroll** (67.44). **Seiya Suzuki** draws a juicy matchup against Buehler (5.19 xERA), while **Corbin Carroll** remains a critical component of our stolen base strategy, despite the risk associated with facing an Elite Hold pitcher. **Brice Turang** also earns a strong endorsement; his 60.89 score is buoyed by a favorable matchup against the slow-delivering Kelly, creating a high-probability environment for him to swipe a bag.\n\nThe most difficult bench decision today involved **Travis Bazzana**, who narrowly missed the cut with a 50.78 score. While **Travis Bazzana** posted strong marks against the 4.59 xERA of Martinez, he fell victim to the depth of our middle infield and outfield options, specifically losing out to the higher-upside profiles of **Mickey Moniak** and **Tyler Soderstrom**. Meanwhile, **Jose Caballero** was an easy scratch, falling below our 40.0 floor due to the brutal matchup against deGrom. We are exercising caution with **Jazz Chisholm Jr.** and **Austin Riley** as well; both face pitchers with high hold percentages (64% and 40% respectively), meaning that while they are starting, their paths to stolen base production are heavily restricted today. \n\nOwners should keep a close eye on weather and late-scratch reports, as our floor for **Luis Campusano** (41.66) is precarious. While **Dalton Rushing** is locked into the leadoff spot and offers a solid 58.60, his performance against Junk will be the barometer for our early-game offensive production. We are effectively punting on the upside of **Alex Freeland** and **Kyle Karros** today, prioritizing the higher-efficiency projections of our starters over the speculative value of our bench depth. Remain vigilant regarding **Trevor Story** and **Josh Naylor**, as both are facing mid-tier arms where small variances in park factor will dictate whether they hit or miss their projected outputs.",
